body:
## Steps to reproduce the issue

Consider the following design:

```verilog
//
// a should have the value 1'b0 if it is not connected to a driving value
//	by the instantiating module.  Otherwise, it should have the
//	value given by the instantiating core
module mcvrinit(input wire a = 1'b0, output wire b);
	assign	b = a;

	// This should succeed if mcvrinit is the top-level
	// within the proof
	always @(*)
		cover(b != 1'b0);

endmodule

module parent(output wire b);
	mcvrinit initdefault(.b(b));

	// This should always succeed
	//	Since initdefault.a has not been bound, it should
	//	retain its initial value
	always @(*)
		assert(!b);
endmodule

module parentdef(output wire b);
	mcvrinit initdefault(.a(1'b1), .b(b));

	// This should always suceed
	//	Since initdefault.a has now been bound to one,
	//	it should override any initial value
	always @(*)
		assert(b);
endmodule
```

and sby file

```verilog
[tasks]
prf
cvr
prf2

[options]
prf: mode prove
cvr: mode cover
prf2: mode prove
depth 3

[engines]
smtbmc

[script]
read -formal initdefault.sv
prf: prep -top parent
cvr: prep -top mcvrinit
prf2: prep -top parentdef

[files]
initdefault.sv
```

## Expected behavior

I expect all three tests and their associated properties to pass

1. The cover statement, checking whether b (really a) can be non-zero.  When `mcvrinit` is the top level, the default input value should be 'x in spite of whatever default is given.  When `parent` is the top level, this cover statement should fail.  (The failure is not checked by the sby file above)

2. The assertion in parent should also pass.  In this case, the parent or instantiating module is not overriding the value of `a`, so it should be equal to one and hence so should `b`.

3. The assertion in `parentdef` should also pass.  In this case, the default behavior has been overridden by the parent, and so `b==1` should always be true.

See IEEE Std 1800-2012 (the 2012 SVA standard), section 23.2.2.4 "Default port values" for more information regarding the expected behavior.

## Actual behavior

Yosys (without Verific) assumes `a == 0` independent of the context.  As a result, the cover statement fails, the `parent` assertion passes whereas the `parentdef` assertion fails.

